<span id="freeTextContainer16950034953371859215">“Rain of Gold”, by Victor Villasenor, was given to me by a good friend who told me that it is his favorite book. I don’t normally read non-fiction, but I was hooked from the first page. It reads like a novel, something Villasenor understood before he undertook writing this family history: that some of what happened was so spectacular that it would seem unbelievable! But his research showed him otherwise. <br/><br/>“Rain of Gold” is VERY fast-paced. Something is always happening; it is action-packed! It’s </span>
  <span id="freeText16950034953371859215" style="display:none">“Rain of Gold”, by Victor Villasenor, was given to me by a good friend who told me that it is his favorite book. I don’t normally read non-fiction, but I was hooked from the first page. It reads like a novel, something Villasenor understood before he undertook writing this family history: that some of what happened was so spectacular that it would seem unbelievable! But his research showed him otherwise. <br /><br />“Rain of Gold” is VERY fast-paced. Something is always happening; it is action-packed! It’s also full of love and loss, faith, and endurance. <br /><br />For a modern look at a similar subject I highly recommend the novel, “American Dirt”, by Jeanine Cummins.<br /></span>
